<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A relatively distinct cerrado species with the characteristically shortly petiolate leaves of an erect or ascending species. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirsutissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea hirsutissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. aurifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in habit but is distinguished by the pubescent indumentum, ovate leaves and sepals, and shortly pedicellate white flowers borne in small axillary cymes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rondônia">Rondonia</normalizedToken>
collection, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Veira et al.</emphasis>
783, is somewhat anomalous having slightly larger sepals and pink flowers (according to the collection label). In habit and other details it fits 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerradoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea cerradoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is probably correctly placed here unless further collections from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rondônia">Rondonia</normalizedToken>
prove otherwise.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
